1
00:03:39,386 --> 00:03:43,755
MAN: All ready here, sir. Crew standing by
and awaiting your word. Over.

2
00:03:59,322 --> 00:04:01,359
Right. Over and out.

3
00:04:07,497 --> 00:04:09,488
[SIREN WAILING]

4
00:04:12,669 --> 00:04:15,832
MAN : Our man was brought down
at <i>2</i> a.m. this morning.

5
00:04:16,006 --> 00:04:20,170
SHAEF, in their all-knowing wisdom,
didn't let us know until 10 a.m.

6
00:04:20,343 --> 00:04:23,301
Damned idiots.
Damned idiots for not letting us know.

7
00:04:23,472 --> 00:04:27,010
Double damned idiots
for ignoring our advice in the first place.

8
00:04:27,184 --> 00:04:29,516
Anyway, here he is...

9
00:04:30,353 --> 00:04:32,185
...in a town called Werfen...

10
00:04:32,355 --> 00:04:35,973
...at the Schloss Adler,
the Castle of the Eagles.

11
00:04:36,151 --> 00:04:39,815
And believe me, it's well-named,
because only an eagle can get to it.

12
00:04:40,614 --> 00:04:44,858
Our job is to get inside there
and get him out as soon as possible...

13
00:04:45,035 --> 00:04:47,276
...before they can
get the information from him.

14
00:04:47,454 --> 00:04:50,162
How are you so sure that he's there, sir?

15
00:04:50,332 --> 00:04:53,700
The Mosquito he was in
crash-landed only 1O miles away.

16
00:04:53,877 --> 00:04:57,871
The Schloss Adler is the headquarters of the
German secret service in southern Bavaria.

17
00:04:58,298 --> 00:05:00,255
Where else would they take him?

18
00:05:00,425 --> 00:05:04,009
- How did the plane crash, sir?
-Through the most damnable ill luck.

19
00:05:04,179 --> 00:05:07,342
We carried out a saturation raid
on Nuremberg last night.

20
00:05:07,516 --> 00:05:11,510
There shouldn't have been a German fighter
within 100 miles of the Austrian border.

21
00:05:11,686 --> 00:05:14,223
A wandering Messerschmitt patrol
got him.

22
00:05:14,481 --> 00:05:16,893
Anyway, that's not important.

23
00:05:17,192 --> 00:05:21,607
What is important is that
we get him out before he talks.

24
00:05:22,364 --> 00:05:25,698
Or I should say, you get him out.

25
00:05:25,867 --> 00:05:28,029
What about paratroops, sir?

26
00:05:28,203 --> 00:05:31,867
The Schloss Adler
is inaccessible and impregnable.

27
00:05:32,457 --> 00:05:35,074
It would require a battalion
of paratroops to take it.

28
00:05:35,252 --> 00:05:36,913
We haven't got the time.

29
00:05:37,295 --> 00:05:39,787
Stealth and secrecy are our only hope...

30
00:05:40,382 --> 00:05:43,716
...and you gentlemen are,
I trust, stealthy and secretive.

31
00:05:43,885 --> 00:05:47,628
We realize of course that you've never
worked together before as a team...

32
00:05:47,848 --> 00:05:52,137
...but you're familiar with one another,
except for Lieutenant Schaffer here.

33
00:05:52,602 --> 00:05:54,764
You probably noticed
that Lieutenant Schaffer...

34
00:05:54,938 --> 00:05:57,896
...wears the shoulder flashes
of the American Ranger division.

35
00:05:58,191 --> 00:06:00,432
I think that speaks for itself.

36
00:06:00,902 --> 00:06:02,939
Major Smith will lead the group in.

37
00:06:03,113 --> 00:06:06,401
Now, you're all expert
at survival behind enemy lines.

38
00:06:06,616 --> 00:06:08,198
Smith, Lieutenant Schaffer...

39
00:06:08,368 --> 00:06:11,611
...Sergeants Harrod and MacPherson
in their military capacities...

40
00:06:11,788 --> 00:06:14,906
...the rest of you in other duties.

41
00:06:15,083 --> 00:06:17,324
You all speak fluent German.

42
00:06:17,502 --> 00:06:20,335
You've been trained
in different types of combat.

43
00:06:20,922 --> 00:06:24,131
If anybody has a chance
of getting him out, you have.

44
00:06:24,342 --> 00:06:26,458
There is, of course, another way, sir.

45
00:06:26,636 --> 00:06:29,970
A way with a 100 percent guarantee
of success.

46
00:06:30,140 --> 00:06:34,885
Neither Admiral Rolland or I
claim to be omniscient or infallible.

47
00:06:35,061 --> 00:06:37,428
Is there an alternative that we've missed?

48
00:06:37,606 --> 00:06:41,975
Whistle up a pathfinder squadron
of Lancasters with 10-ton bombs.

49
00:06:42,819 --> 00:06:45,811
I don't think anybody in that castle
would ever talk again.

50
00:06:45,989 --> 00:06:48,822
Nor do I think that you grasp
the realities of the situation.

51
00:06:49,326 --> 00:06:52,489
The captured man, General Carnaby,
is an American.

52
00:06:52,829 --> 00:06:55,662
If we were to destroy him,
then I think General Eisenhower...

53
00:06:55,832 --> 00:06:59,450
...might launch his second front against us
rather than against the Germans.

54
00:06:59,628 --> 00:07:04,373
There are certain niceties to be observed
in our relationship with our allies.

55
00:07:06,384 --> 00:07:10,844
Very well, then, gentlemen.
Ten o'clock tonight at the airfield.

56
00:07:11,348 --> 00:07:14,340
- No more questions, I take it?
-Yes, sir.

57
00:07:14,684 --> 00:07:18,177
Begging the colonel's pardon, sir.
What's all this about?

58
00:07:18,355 --> 00:07:20,517
I mean, why is this man
so damned important?

59
00:07:20,815 --> 00:07:22,522
- Why should--?
-That'll do, sergeant.

60
00:07:22,692 --> 00:07:24,683
You have all the information you require.

61
00:07:24,861 --> 00:07:27,694
I think if we're sending a man
to what may be his death...

62
00:07:27,864 --> 00:07:30,196
...he has a right to know why.

63
00:07:30,408 --> 00:07:32,490
It's painfully simple, sergeant.

64
00:07:33,328 --> 00:07:36,195
General Carnaby is one
of the overall coordinators...

65
00:07:36,373 --> 00:07:38,740
...of planning for the second front.

66
00:07:39,042 --> 00:07:43,036
He set out last night to meet
his opposite numbers in the Middle East...

67
00:07:43,213 --> 00:07:46,001
...to finalize the plans
for the invasion of Europe.

68
00:07:46,383 --> 00:07:49,091
The rendezvous with the Russians
was to have been in Crete.

69
00:07:49,594 --> 00:07:52,052
Now, unfortunately, his plane
didn't get through.

70
00:07:52,722 --> 00:07:57,808
Now, if the Germans can make him talk...

71
00:07:57,978 --> 00:08:00,561
...it could mean no second front
this year.

72
00:08:00,730 --> 00:08:04,894
- Do you understand, sergeant?
-Yes, sir.

73
00:08:05,485 --> 00:08:08,773
- I'm sorry, sir.
TURNER: That's all right, sergeant. Forget it.

74
00:08:08,947 --> 00:08:12,030
Now, if you have any more questions,
Major Smith will answer them.

75
00:08:12,534 --> 00:08:14,275
That's all, gentlemen.

76
00:08:44,024 --> 00:08:46,516
PILOT: Get them ready.
We're approaching the drop area.

77
00:08:46,693 --> 00:08:48,525
Stand by!

78
00:09:06,129 --> 00:09:07,995
Green on! Go!

79
00:11:38,656 --> 00:11:40,192
<i>Where's Hatred'?</i>

80
00:11:44,078 --> 00:11:48,993
Well, last time I saw him, he was drifting
towards those trees over here.

81
00:11:53,588 --> 00:11:56,671
All right. Spread out.

82
00:11:56,841 --> 00:11:58,002
Let's go and find him.

83
00:12:27,330 --> 00:12:29,162
Major!

84
00:13:14,544 --> 00:13:17,662
- His neck's broken.
-Damn it.

85
00:13:21,843 --> 00:13:25,211
Well, what do we do now?
Do we bury him or do we leave him here?

86
00:13:25,388 --> 00:13:28,881
We leave him here. The snow
will cover him in a couple of hours.

87
00:13:29,058 --> 00:13:33,177
Get back and pick up the equipment.
I want to see if the radio's still working.

88
00:15:14,664 --> 00:15:16,154
Well...

89
00:15:16,499 --> 00:15:19,912
...the radio works all right. There's a barn
about a mile down the valley.

90
00:15:20,086 --> 00:15:22,043
We'll use it to check our equipment.

91
00:15:22,213 --> 00:15:24,830
- What about the people who live in it?
-There aren't any.

92
00:15:25,007 --> 00:15:27,294
This is a high alpine pasture.

93
00:15:27,760 --> 00:15:30,673
They bring the cattle up in May
and take them down in September.

94
00:15:31,013 --> 00:15:33,801
The rest of the time,
the place is totally deserted.

95
00:15:33,975 --> 00:15:36,433
Come on. Let's go.

96
00:16:10,761 --> 00:16:13,719
Somehow, you know, this just isn't me.

97
00:16:13,890 --> 00:16:17,633
It's not any of us, Jock.
You're the cook. Cook...

98
00:16:17,810 --> 00:16:22,896
...some hot food and some hot coffee,
and then call London on the radio.

99
00:16:23,065 --> 00:16:25,682
Damn it. I left that codebook
in Sergeant Harrods tunic.

100
00:16:25,860 --> 00:16:29,694
<i>- I'll</i> go and get it for you.
- No, it's all right. It's my own stupid fault.

101
00:16:29,864 --> 00:16:33,573
Sounds as if it's still blowing a blizzard.
Yeah.

102
00:16:34,076 --> 00:16:36,317
Well, if I'm not back in an hour...

103
00:16:36,496 --> 00:16:39,409
...signal me with a flare pistol
four times every five minutes.

104
00:16:39,582 --> 00:16:41,243
That should bring a blind man home.

105
00:16:41,417 --> 00:16:43,829
Might also bring the best part
of a German regiment.

106
00:16:44,003 --> 00:16:46,540
There's not a German within five miles.

107
00:16:46,714 --> 00:16:49,126
Nobody leaves here until I come back.

108
00:16:49,300 --> 00:16:52,463
- Jock, save me some coffee.
-It'll be cold by then.

109
00:16:53,137 --> 00:16:56,425
They say that's an advantage.
You can't taste cold coffee.

110
00:17:49,819 --> 00:17:51,150
[GUN CLICKS]

111
00:18:17,346 --> 00:18:18,632
WOMAN:
Halt.

112
00:18:19,515 --> 00:18:21,381
Turn around.

113
00:18:29,400 --> 00:18:32,313
You took your time getting here,
didn't you?

114
00:18:32,778 --> 00:18:34,815
Things to attend to.

115
00:18:35,740 --> 00:18:37,356
- You enjoy your trip?
-Lovely.

116
00:18:37,533 --> 00:18:39,649
I nearly froze to death
in that damn plane.

117
00:18:39,827 --> 00:18:44,412
Why couldn't you have supplied some hot
water bottles or an electrically heated suit?

118
00:18:44,582 --> 00:18:48,496
- I thought you loved me.
-I can't help what you think.

119
00:18:48,669 --> 00:18:50,785
You managed to bring your gear.

120
00:18:50,963 --> 00:18:52,954
Is that all the greeting I'm going to get?

121
00:18:53,132 --> 00:18:57,421
I'm afraid so, for the time being.
My radio operator was killed in the drop.

122
00:18:57,595 --> 00:18:59,336
What happened?

123
00:18:59,555 --> 00:19:01,637
Something struck him
in the back of the neck.

124
00:19:01,807 --> 00:19:04,014
Either the haft of a knife
or the butt of a gun.

125
00:19:04,185 --> 00:19:06,176
The skin was unbroken,
but badly discolored.

126
00:19:06,354 --> 00:19:08,436
It means someone
broke his neck afterwards...

127
00:19:08,606 --> 00:19:10,392
...to make it look like an accident.

128
00:19:10,566 --> 00:19:14,400
Now listen, I'm taking the group at dawn
over the ridge into the next valley.

129
00:19:14,570 --> 00:19:17,608
We'll stop in the woods until about 7.
Now, don't stumble into us.

130
00:19:18,574 --> 00:19:21,362
As soon as it's dark,
we'll move into the village of Werfen.

131
00:19:21,535 --> 00:19:24,402
In the village, there's a gasthaus
called Zum Wilden Hirsch.

132
00:19:24,872 --> 00:19:27,364
Behind it and to the right,
there's a woodshed.

133
00:19:27,541 --> 00:19:31,125
I'll meet you there
at exactly 8:00 tomorrow night.

134
00:19:32,421 --> 00:19:35,334
- And after that, what?
<i>- I'll</i> let you know when the time comes.

135
00:19:35,508 --> 00:19:36,873
Ah.

136
00:19:37,301 --> 00:19:40,259
- I see you've come fully prepared.
-Never mind about that.

137
00:19:40,429 --> 00:19:44,969
How do you know about all these things,
Zum Wilden Hirsch and the shed?

138
00:19:46,602 --> 00:19:47,933
I'm entitled to know.

139
00:19:48,771 --> 00:19:50,728
You're entitled to know nothing.

140
00:19:53,150 --> 00:19:55,812
We've worked together for three years.
I'm a professional.

141
00:19:55,986 --> 00:19:57,021
So am I.

142
00:19:57,446 --> 00:20:00,279
If I were the marrying kind, which I'm--

143
00:20:06,872 --> 00:20:10,615
- I thought you were in a hurry.
-So I am.

144
00:20:10,793 --> 00:20:12,500
Aren't you?

145
00:21:19,904 --> 00:21:21,770
SCHAFFER:
What kept you?

146
00:21:22,072 --> 00:21:24,814
Well, I was very lucky.

147
00:21:24,992 --> 00:21:29,611
I ran into this fabulous blond.
She was lying on a snowdrift.

148
00:21:29,789 --> 00:21:31,200
Does she have a friend?

149
00:21:31,373 --> 00:21:33,785
No, I'm afraid you're out of luck.

150
00:21:34,710 --> 00:21:38,829
- Thanks for waiting up for me, anyway.
-No problem.

151
00:21:51,894 --> 00:21:53,885
Lieutenant, why don't you go to sleep?

152
00:21:54,063 --> 00:21:56,430
It'll be dawn in a couple of hours.
You too, Jock.

153
00:21:56,607 --> 00:21:58,143
Yeah, I'll do that.

154
00:22:00,528 --> 00:22:02,519
[STATIC BUZZING ON RADIO]

155
00:22:06,951 --> 00:22:08,908
Can't get a thing.

156
00:22:11,247 --> 00:22:12,453
Probably the storm, huh?

157
00:22:13,958 --> 00:22:15,164
Yeah.

158
00:22:15,334 --> 00:22:17,746
Yeah, we'll try again in the morning.

159
00:22:54,748 --> 00:22:58,457
Lieutenant, come with me.
The rest of you stay here.

160
00:23:14,476 --> 00:23:16,683
Better leave the equipment here.

161
00:23:45,633 --> 00:23:48,000
Somebody's got to be crazy.

162
00:23:48,844 --> 00:23:51,176
How'd your colonel
expect anyone to get in there?

163
00:23:51,347 --> 00:23:53,839
He feels if he can penetrate
the German High Command...

164
00:23:54,016 --> 00:23:56,053
...we shouldn't have difficulty
getting up.

165
00:23:56,226 --> 00:23:57,967
He did what?

166
00:23:58,354 --> 00:24:01,472
He spent the years '40 to '43
in Germany, first in the Wehrmacht...

167
00:24:01,649 --> 00:24:04,516
...and then finally
in General Headquarters in Berlin.

168
00:24:04,693 --> 00:24:07,025
They say he knew Hitler quite well.

169
00:24:07,196 --> 00:24:09,858
- I thought he looked a little nuts.
-Yeah, probably is.

170
00:24:10,032 --> 00:24:13,070
Now we've got problems of our own.
Get the boys into the trees.

171
00:24:13,243 --> 00:24:16,577
We've brought them too far over.
Be sure they go beyond that tree line.

172
00:24:16,747 --> 00:24:19,034
- And what about you?
<i>- I'll</i> be along in a minute.

173
00:24:19,208 --> 00:24:22,417
- Be sure they stay behind the trees.
-All right.

174
00:25:24,064 --> 00:25:28,524
Broadsword calling Danny Boy.
Broadsword calling Danny Boy. Over.

175
00:25:29,611 --> 00:25:32,729
MAN <i>[OVER RADIO]: Danny Boy calling
Broadsword. Father Machree is waiting.</i>

176
00:25:33,532 --> 00:25:35,773
This is Father Machree, Broadsword.

177
00:25:35,951 --> 00:25:38,534
What is your present position, please?
Over.

178
00:25:39,371 --> 00:25:43,956
Woods due west of castle.
Descending at dusk. Harrod dead.

179
00:25:44,251 --> 00:25:45,867
Over.

180
00:25:46,670 --> 00:25:50,789
Was Harrod killed accidentally? Over.

181
00:25:50,966 --> 00:25:53,003
<i>No. Over.</i>

182
00:25:53,177 --> 00:25:55,088
By the Germans? Over.

183
00:25:55,512 --> 00:25:56,968
No.

184
00:25:57,139 --> 00:26:00,598
Time of next broadcast uncertain.
Will you stand by?

185
00:26:01,060 --> 00:26:02,642
Over.

186
00:26:02,811 --> 00:26:06,645
Colonel Turner and I will remain
at headquarters till operation completed.

187
00:26:06,815 --> 00:26:09,307
Good luck. Out.

188
00:26:19,703 --> 00:26:21,865
It looks as though you're right, sir.

189
00:26:22,873 --> 00:26:25,331
Yes, I'm afraid so.

190
00:26:25,501 --> 00:26:27,538
Who's next, I wonder?

191
00:26:27,711 --> 00:26:28,997
Smith himself, perhaps.

192
00:26:29,963 --> 00:26:34,673
I doubt that.
Some people have a sixth sense.

193
00:26:34,843 --> 00:26:37,460
He has a sixth, a seventh and an eighth.

194
00:26:37,679 --> 00:26:41,217
- He's our best agent.
-Except yourself.

195
00:26:42,851 --> 00:26:47,561
Still and all, even if he is the best,
this whole operation looks impossible now.

196
00:27:28,856 --> 00:27:31,848
SCHAFFER: Take a look down there,
at the foot of the castle.

197
00:27:33,026 --> 00:27:34,482
[DOG BARKING]

198
00:27:34,653 --> 00:27:36,235
SMITH:
Dobermans.

199
00:27:36,405 --> 00:27:40,649
Yeah. Dobermans, a guard tower
and a wire fence.

200
00:27:40,826 --> 00:27:43,784
Fences can be cut or climbed, lieutenant.

201
00:27:43,954 --> 00:27:48,869
I doubt if that one can be climbed. It's got
around 3,000 volts running through it.

202
00:27:49,042 --> 00:27:52,080
If I'm not mistaken, major,
that's an army barracks over there.

203
00:27:54,840 --> 00:27:58,253
SMITH: No mistake. This is the headquarters
of the Wehrmacht Alpenkorps.

204
00:27:58,802 --> 00:28:02,261
Swell. If you got any other surprises,
I think I ought to know about them.

205
00:28:02,431 --> 00:28:04,138
I thought you knew, lieutenant.

206
00:28:04,308 --> 00:28:06,766
Why do you think
we're not dressed as German sailors?

207
00:28:06,935 --> 00:28:08,926
Training troops come and go all the time.

208
00:28:09,104 --> 00:28:11,596
What are six new faces
among 600 new faces?

209
00:28:11,773 --> 00:28:14,936
Look, major,
this is primarily a British operation.

210
00:28:15,110 --> 00:28:17,943
I'm an American.
I don't even know why the hell I'm here.

211
00:28:18,113 --> 00:28:20,571
Lieutenant, you're here
because you're an American.

212
00:28:20,741 --> 00:28:22,732
[AIRCRAFT DRONING]

213
00:29:43,949 --> 00:29:46,941
Dear Kramer, you have turned
a little gray since I saw you last.

214
00:29:47,119 --> 00:29:49,076
I'm afraid so, sir.

215
00:29:49,496 --> 00:29:51,703
- How is Berlin, sir?
-Things have changed.

216
00:29:51,873 --> 00:29:53,204
You like my machine?

217
00:29:53,375 --> 00:29:56,117
- It looks pretty dangerous.
-Well, you must try it.

218
00:29:56,295 --> 00:29:58,912
Major Burkhalter, my adjutant.

219
00:29:59,089 --> 00:30:02,252
Major Brant, Jaeger Battalion.

220
00:30:02,426 --> 00:30:06,010
Colonel Weissner, Field Security.

221
00:30:06,388 --> 00:30:09,426
Major Von Hapen, Gestapo.

222
00:30:16,398 --> 00:30:20,266
- Have you questioned him yet?
-No. I was waiting for you.

223
00:30:20,444 --> 00:30:23,857
That Major Von Hapen,
does he know General Carnaby's here?

224
00:30:24,031 --> 00:30:27,899
Yes. I did inform him of his arrival,
but not of his importance.

225
00:30:28,076 --> 00:30:31,569
Good. If possible, I'd prefer the Gestapo
to be kept out of this matter...

226
00:30:31,747 --> 00:30:34,114
...until we have the information we want.
-Fine.

227
00:30:34,291 --> 00:30:37,158
We don't need them cluttering up things
with torture chambers.

228
00:30:37,336 --> 00:30:40,078
This can remain a strictly army matter
for the time being.

229
00:30:40,255 --> 00:30:41,745
- I agree.
-Good.

230
00:30:41,923 --> 00:30:45,757
I've had a very tiring trip down here
from Berlin. I'd like to freshen up a bit.

231
00:30:45,927 --> 00:30:48,589
Perhaps sleep a few hours
before meeting General Carnaby.

232
00:30:48,764 --> 00:30:51,096
KRAMER: I'll see you to your quarters.
ROSEMEYER: Thank you.

233
00:30:51,266 --> 00:30:53,758
The meeting will be ready
whenever you wish.

234
00:30:53,935 --> 00:30:55,471
ROSEMEYER:
Tell me...

235
00:33:00,437 --> 00:33:02,428
[MEN LAUGHING]

236
00:33:31,259 --> 00:33:33,250
[VEHICLE APPROACHING]

237
00:34:18,139 --> 00:34:20,096
GUARD:
Show me your papers.

238
00:34:27,857 --> 00:34:28,892
Right.

239
00:34:29,067 --> 00:34:32,276
I've written her many times
of course, but...

240
00:34:32,445 --> 00:34:36,985
...with so many troops on leave in Berlin,
it was hardly likely she'd remember me.

241
00:34:37,200 --> 00:34:39,862
But one always hopes
you're the one she'll never forget.

242
00:34:40,036 --> 00:34:42,118
Yeah. What was her name, anyway?

243
00:34:42,289 --> 00:34:44,280
- Fred.
-Fred?

244
00:34:44,457 --> 00:34:48,826
Oh, yeah, I remember Fred, yeah.
She was a short little redhead.

245
00:35:23,788 --> 00:35:26,155
We'll try this one behind us.

246
00:35:26,333 --> 00:35:28,290
When you get inside, circulate around.

247
00:35:28,460 --> 00:35:31,373
Keep your ears open for anything
about General Carnaby.

248
00:35:32,380 --> 00:35:36,169
We meet back here
in half an hour. All right.

249
00:35:47,312 --> 00:35:49,303
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

250
00:35:49,481 --> 00:35:51,438
[BAND PLAYING POLKA MUSIC]

251
00:36:23,348 --> 00:36:24,930
SCHAFFER:
Two beers.

252
00:36:30,438 --> 00:36:32,429
[LAUGHING]

253
00:36:33,942 --> 00:36:35,273
Ah.

254
00:36:43,785 --> 00:36:45,776
See you later.

255
00:37:00,885 --> 00:37:02,796
Anything else needed here? Oh.

256
00:37:02,971 --> 00:37:05,838
And who might you be,
my pretty alpine rose?

257
00:37:06,015 --> 00:37:09,428
- Heidi. Stop, major. I've got work.
-There's no more important work...

258
00:37:09,602 --> 00:37:11,969
...than entertaining
the soldiers of the fatherland.

259
00:37:12,147 --> 00:37:14,809
- Shall I sing you a song?
-I hear too much singing.

260
00:37:14,983 --> 00:37:18,146
Oh, very well, then. I'll whistle.
it goes like this:

261
00:37:18,319 --> 00:37:20,481
[WHISTLING]

262
00:37:21,531 --> 00:37:23,021
[LAUGHING]

263
00:37:23,199 --> 00:37:26,191
I bet you have
a beautiful singing voice too.

264
00:37:26,369 --> 00:37:27,985
Thank you.

265
00:37:28,163 --> 00:37:31,155
Be in the woodshed in five minutes.

266
00:37:31,833 --> 00:37:33,699
Now slap me across the face
as hard as you can.

267
00:37:34,043 --> 00:37:35,659
Oh!

268
00:37:39,340 --> 00:37:41,001
OFFICER:
Major...

269
00:37:41,426 --> 00:37:44,418
...your conduct does not become
an officer of the Wehrmacht.

270
00:37:45,680 --> 00:37:48,342
Herr Major, when you talk to me.

271
00:37:48,516 --> 00:37:52,009
Major Bernd Himmler.
Does the name mean anything to you?

272
00:37:53,730 --> 00:37:56,939
I advise you to mind
your own business in future.

273
00:37:57,358 --> 00:37:59,440
Is that understood?

274
00:38:13,416 --> 00:38:16,534
- Cognac.
-Make that two.

275
00:38:16,711 --> 00:38:20,045
I don't suppose you found out anything
about General Carnaby.

276
00:38:20,256 --> 00:38:22,247
I didn't get around to that. Thank you.

277
00:38:22,425 --> 00:38:25,042
What were you and that major
talking about?

278
00:38:25,345 --> 00:38:28,007
I told him I was Himmler's brother.

279
00:38:29,307 --> 00:38:31,890
Yeah, I could see why that would
shake him up a little.

280
00:38:32,060 --> 00:38:34,051
More than a little, I should think.

281
00:38:34,229 --> 00:38:36,516
Keep an eye on things. I'll be back.

282
00:39:42,839 --> 00:39:44,125
Take your clothes off.

283
00:39:44,299 --> 00:39:48,167
- But I--
-Don't argue. Take your clothes off.

284
00:39:50,722 --> 00:39:52,429
MARY:
All right.

285
00:39:54,851 --> 00:39:58,810
Now, relax. I didn't mean it that way.

286
00:40:00,273 --> 00:40:04,767
You are going up to the castle tonight as--
Well, yes, as a domestic.

287
00:40:05,653 --> 00:40:07,564
How? Naked?

288
00:40:07,739 --> 00:40:09,821
Not a bad idea, but it's a bit obvious.

289
00:40:09,991 --> 00:40:15,077
There's an acute staff shortage in Germany
and the Schloss Adler is no exception.

290
00:40:16,581 --> 00:40:19,994
You're the type they're looking for:
young, intelligent, good-looking...

291
00:40:20,168 --> 00:40:22,500
...and as we both know,
not entirely without humor.

292
00:40:22,670 --> 00:40:23,956
You must be mad.

293
00:40:24,130 --> 00:40:26,667
If I wasn't, what would I be doing
in this job?

294
00:40:26,841 --> 00:40:28,502
Now listen very carefully.

295
00:40:28,676 --> 00:40:32,169
You're supposed to arrive on a bus
from Steingaden in about 2O minutes.

296
00:40:32,347 --> 00:40:35,385
Your name is Maria Schenk.
You come from the Rhineland.

297
00:40:35,600 --> 00:40:37,341
Here, give me that boot.

298
00:40:37,810 --> 00:40:40,177
You've had TB and were forced
to give up your job.

299
00:40:40,355 --> 00:40:43,222
You have a cousin called Heidi
who works in Zum Wilden Hirsch.

300
00:40:43,399 --> 00:40:45,356
It's because of her that you got the job.

301
00:40:45,526 --> 00:40:48,393
- Where are my identity papers?
-In that case...

302
00:40:48,571 --> 00:40:51,905
...together with your travel permit.
Heidi will give you the rest later.

303
00:40:52,075 --> 00:40:54,533
It must have taken time
to prepare these things.

304
00:40:54,702 --> 00:40:57,945
Very likely. Our Forgery Department
did a special job on your papers.

305
00:40:59,457 --> 00:41:04,042
But I thought General Carnaby's
plane crashed only yesterday morning.

306
00:41:04,212 --> 00:41:05,953
It was carefully arranged.

307
00:41:06,172 --> 00:41:09,130
The plane was crash-landed
in Oberhausen Military Airfield...

308
00:41:09,300 --> 00:41:10,836
...about five miles from here.

309
00:41:11,010 --> 00:41:14,423
It was riddled with machine-gun holes,
British machine-gun holes.

310
00:41:14,597 --> 00:41:18,056
But what the hell?
A hole is a hole is a hole, as they say.

311
00:41:18,226 --> 00:41:21,810
Are you trying to say that you'd risk
the life of an American general...

312
00:41:21,980 --> 00:41:24,893
...and all the plans for the second front?
-Of course not.

313
00:41:26,526 --> 00:41:28,483
Give me the other boot.

314
00:41:28,987 --> 00:41:30,898
I'm in a hurry to get to the castle...

315
00:41:31,072 --> 00:41:34,030
...before they find out
they haven't got General Carnaby.

316
00:41:34,200 --> 00:41:36,942
The chap they've got knows no more
about the second front...

317
00:41:37,120 --> 00:41:41,409
...than I know about the back end of
the moon. He's an American corporal.

318
00:41:41,582 --> 00:41:43,118
His name is Cartwright Jones.

319
00:41:43,292 --> 00:41:45,579
He's an ex-actor, probably second-rate...

320
00:41:45,753 --> 00:41:48,085
...but he's the dead spitting image
of the general.

321
00:41:48,256 --> 00:41:51,294
Did you talk this poor man
into getting involved with all this?

322
00:41:51,467 --> 00:41:54,960
I didn't have to. He volunteered.
What actor wouldn't?

323
00:41:56,014 --> 00:42:00,178
If he pulls this off, it'll be
the summit of his professional career.

324
00:42:00,560 --> 00:42:02,892
Mind you,
it might be a short engagement.

325
00:42:03,187 --> 00:42:05,303
Yes. A one-night stand.

326
00:42:05,481 --> 00:42:06,812
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

327
00:42:22,123 --> 00:42:23,454
Ah.

328
00:42:23,666 --> 00:42:24,872
Well, here we are.

329
00:42:25,043 --> 00:42:27,034
Mary, now Maria,
this is your cousin Heidi.

330
00:42:27,211 --> 00:42:31,205
Leave this behind in case you're searched.
Heidi will tell you what to do from now on.

331
00:42:31,466 --> 00:42:36,302
She's been one of our top agents
in Bavaria since 1941 and...

332
00:42:36,804 --> 00:42:38,966
What a disguise.

333
00:43:26,562 --> 00:43:28,473
So he left three minutes after me...

334
00:43:28,648 --> 00:43:32,812
...in a hurry, you say,
so he wasn't after me.

335
00:43:33,236 --> 00:43:34,852
Any of the others leave?

336
00:43:35,196 --> 00:43:37,654
Not that I could see,
but this place is so crowded...

337
00:43:37,824 --> 00:43:40,065
...and there are several other exits.

338
00:43:40,243 --> 00:43:42,735
Any one of them could have slipped out.

339
00:43:44,205 --> 00:43:47,823
You better start playing it straight
or you can deal me out of this mess.

340
00:43:48,543 --> 00:43:52,081
Now, we both know that radio operator
wasn't killed in any drop.

341
00:43:52,839 --> 00:43:56,252
Now, with MacPherson dead,
there's only five of us left.

342
00:43:56,634 --> 00:44:00,298
You either let me know what's going on
or there's only gonna be four.

343
00:44:00,471 --> 00:44:01,927
All right, lieutenant.

344
00:44:02,098 --> 00:44:06,387
This morning you asked me why you,
an American, was on this mission.

345
00:44:06,686 --> 00:44:09,929
Well, the answer is really very simple.

346
00:44:13,818 --> 00:44:15,434
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

347
00:44:15,611 --> 00:44:17,352
Maria.

348
00:44:17,655 --> 00:44:20,568
Oh, my dear Maria, you came after all.

349
00:44:20,741 --> 00:44:24,154
My dear cousin Heidi, how wonderful
to see you after all these years.

350
00:44:24,328 --> 00:44:27,821
Gestapo. I am so happy to see you.

351
00:44:27,999 --> 00:44:31,583
May I introduce you to a friend of mine?
Major Von Hapen.

352
00:44:31,752 --> 00:44:34,335
My cousin Maria Schenk.

353
00:44:35,506 --> 00:44:39,670
Your cousin told us to expect you,
Fréulein Schenk, but Heidi...

354
00:44:39,844 --> 00:44:42,336
...you did not tell me
she was as beautiful as this.

355
00:44:42,513 --> 00:44:44,174
Thank you.

356
00:44:44,432 --> 00:44:47,720
Perhaps when you're ready
to take the cable car to the castle...

357
00:44:47,894 --> 00:44:50,135
...I'll have the honor to escort you.
MARY: Thank you.

358
00:44:50,313 --> 00:44:52,475
And I am going with her.

359
00:44:52,815 --> 00:44:53,896
Oh.

360
00:44:54,066 --> 00:44:56,899
Both of you, huh?
Well, then I am very fortunate.

361
00:44:57,069 --> 00:44:58,309
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

362
00:44:58,487 --> 00:45:00,945
Fréulein, until a little bit later.

363
00:45:25,640 --> 00:45:28,223
This is a map of the castle.

364
00:45:29,310 --> 00:45:31,142
And your instructions.

365
00:45:31,312 --> 00:45:32,643
Do your homework well.

366
00:45:36,359 --> 00:45:38,350
[MAN SHOUTING IN GERMAN]

367
00:45:49,705 --> 00:45:51,537
He doesn't seem to be anywhere in here.

368
00:45:51,707 --> 00:45:55,200
Wonder where the devil he's got to.
I gave orders that nobody should leave.

369
00:45:55,378 --> 00:45:57,164
Shall I go outside and take a look?

370
00:45:57,880 --> 00:45:59,837
[WHISTLE BLOWING]

371
00:46:05,388 --> 00:46:07,095
MAN:
Attention. Nobody make a move.

372
00:46:07,265 --> 00:46:10,553
Against the wall, please.
Against the wall.

373
00:46:15,189 --> 00:46:16,771
Attention.

374
00:46:16,941 --> 00:46:20,354
We are looking for four or five
Alpenkorps deserters from Stuttgart.

375
00:46:20,528 --> 00:46:23,361
To escape, they killed two officers
and a guardroom sergeant.

376
00:46:23,531 --> 00:46:25,693
They were last known
to be heading this way.

377
00:46:25,866 --> 00:46:27,948
Clever. Very clever, indeed.

378
00:46:28,119 --> 00:46:33,080
I want the senior officers of Drafts 13,
14 and 15 to come forward at once.

379
00:46:35,042 --> 00:46:36,282
Check their papers.

380
00:46:37,878 --> 00:46:41,041
Well, gentlemen, any suggestions?

381
00:46:45,636 --> 00:46:47,297
Lieutenant?

382
00:46:47,930 --> 00:46:52,470
Well, I think we'll stand a lot better chance
outside than we will in here.

383
00:46:52,893 --> 00:46:54,634
Agreed.

384
00:46:55,271 --> 00:46:57,888
Gentlemen, see you after the war.

385
00:47:05,698 --> 00:47:09,157
These papers are from the Fourth Panzer
Division stationed in Stuttgart.

386
00:47:09,327 --> 00:47:11,034
When were they issued to him?

387
00:47:11,203 --> 00:47:13,570
- Colonel.
-What is it, major?

388
00:47:13,748 --> 00:47:17,742
Myself and the others are the ones you're
looking for. We've come to surrender.

389
00:47:18,294 --> 00:47:20,911
Lieutenant, take the three men away
for questioning.

390
00:47:21,088 --> 00:47:23,329
The officers will come with me.

391
00:47:34,101 --> 00:47:35,933
Excuse me.

392
00:48:02,380 --> 00:48:04,371
[RINGS]

393
00:48:05,966 --> 00:48:08,173
- Yes?
-Major Von Hapen.

394
00:48:09,804 --> 00:48:11,465
Yes, sir.

395
00:48:22,108 --> 00:48:23,769
Fréulein.

396
00:49:15,035 --> 00:49:16,025
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

397
00:49:16,203 --> 00:49:18,661
It's just my shoelaces.

398
00:49:21,625 --> 00:49:23,616
[GRUNTING]

399
00:49:26,213 --> 00:49:27,374
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

400
00:49:33,929 --> 00:49:35,260
[SCREAMS]

401
00:50:36,992 --> 00:50:39,609
- Need to get rid of this thing.
-Yeah.

402
00:50:39,787 --> 00:50:42,279
Over the cliff. Let's push.

403
00:51:02,434 --> 00:51:05,222
Okay. Push.

404
00:51:10,276 --> 00:51:11,983
Push.

405
00:51:14,405 --> 00:51:15,440
And a little more.

406
00:51:40,180 --> 00:51:41,966
Good evening, lieutenant.

407
00:51:42,141 --> 00:51:44,633
This is Miss Schenk. Lieutenant Kernitser.

408
00:51:44,810 --> 00:51:48,303
She is the colonel's secretary
in charge of all the female staff.

409
00:51:48,480 --> 00:51:52,394
Can I see your papers, please?
And yours, Fréulein.

410
00:52:02,077 --> 00:52:04,159
Would you come with me, please?

411
00:52:04,330 --> 00:52:08,198
- Perhaps I'll see you a little later.
-Thank you.

412
00:52:25,726 --> 00:52:26,716
[DOOR OPENS]

413
00:52:29,021 --> 00:52:32,059
Do you find anything interesting, major?

414
00:52:35,736 --> 00:52:39,400
I hear there was some excitement
in the village tonight.

415
00:52:39,573 --> 00:52:41,234
Oh, nothing very serious.

416
00:52:41,408 --> 00:52:44,241
Just the arrest of five army deserters,
that's all.

417
00:52:44,453 --> 00:52:47,571
Not quite. Those were the orders
that were put out.

418
00:52:47,748 --> 00:52:52,242
But actually, they were five British agents
dressed in German uniforms.

419
00:52:52,419 --> 00:52:55,411
British agents? Why wasn't I informed?

420
00:52:55,839 --> 00:52:57,750
I'm informing you now, major.

421
00:52:58,842 --> 00:53:00,583
If you sent out the orders, colonel...

422
00:53:01,512 --> 00:53:04,550
...then you must have known
for some time...

423
00:53:04,723 --> 00:53:08,057
...who they were
and that they were in this district.

424
00:53:08,227 --> 00:53:11,310
We called you in your office
and in your rooms.

425
00:53:11,480 --> 00:53:13,096
You were not there.

426
00:53:13,273 --> 00:53:17,107
Colonel, I don't have to
remind you, do I...

427
00:53:17,277 --> 00:53:20,440
...that I am in charge of all
the Gestapo activities in this area...

428
00:53:20,614 --> 00:53:24,107
...and if there are foreign agents,
then I am to be informed at once!

429
00:53:24,284 --> 00:53:27,743
- You were not here, major.
-Then you find me, colonel.

430
00:53:27,913 --> 00:53:31,497
My duty is to inform you, but not
to search every gasthaus to locate you.

431
00:53:31,667 --> 00:53:34,159
I know your duties...

432
00:53:34,920 --> 00:53:36,706
...and your loyalties.

433
00:53:37,506 --> 00:53:40,624
Let me remind you, major,
that I'm a colonel in the SS...

434
00:53:40,801 --> 00:53:43,668
...and not some lieutenant
you can frighten with your threats!

435
00:53:43,846 --> 00:53:48,636
Your military rank and position
are obvious to me, colonel...

436
00:53:49,309 --> 00:53:53,052
...and so are your attempts to discredit me
with my superiors in Berlin.

437
00:53:53,230 --> 00:53:57,440
If there is any discredit,
you bring it upon yourself.

438
00:53:57,609 --> 00:53:59,350
Good night.

439
00:54:03,115 --> 00:54:05,607
- You better lock the door.
-Sure.

440
00:54:12,332 --> 00:54:14,824
Here are all the things you'll need.

441
00:54:17,171 --> 00:54:21,540
Automatic, field glasses,
ball of string and lead weight.

442
00:54:21,717 --> 00:54:23,799
- You put those things in there?
-A week ago.

443
00:54:23,969 --> 00:54:28,463
- You knew all about this even then?
-Yeah. Good luck, cousin.

444
00:54:38,066 --> 00:54:40,023
We may need these.

445
00:54:40,277 --> 00:54:44,862
I guess it's occurred to you, the Germans
probably know about all this stuff by now.

446
00:54:45,115 --> 00:54:47,106
It did cross my mind.

447
00:54:53,540 --> 00:54:55,872
Broadsword calling Danny Boy.

448
00:54:56,043 --> 00:54:59,707
Broadsword calling Danny Boy. Over.

449
00:55:02,299 --> 00:55:03,630
[OVER RADIO]
<i>Broadsword calling Danny Boy.</i>

450
00:55:03,801 --> 00:55:06,418
<i>Broadsword calling Danny Boy. Over.</i>

451
00:55:07,513 --> 00:55:09,424
MAN:
Broadsword, sir.

452
00:55:10,307 --> 00:55:13,516
Danny Boy calling Broadsword.
Come in, Broadsword. Over.

453
00:55:14,311 --> 00:55:17,724
MacPherson murdered. Thomas,
Christiansen and Berkeley captured.

454
00:55:17,898 --> 00:55:19,889
I'm effecting entrance within the hour.

455
00:55:20,067 --> 00:55:22,900
<i>Please have transport standing by. Over.</i>

456
00:55:23,070 --> 00:55:25,937
Pull out now, Broadsword.
Save yourselves. Over.

457
00:55:26,698 --> 00:55:28,735
You must be joking. Over and out.

458
00:55:28,909 --> 00:55:31,071
That is an order, Broadsword. Over.

459
00:55:31,245 --> 00:55:32,576
[STATIC BUZZING ON RADIO]

460
00:55:32,746 --> 00:55:34,908
Broadsword? Broadsword?

461
00:55:36,166 --> 00:55:38,032
Broadsword?

462
00:55:39,378 --> 00:55:41,085
Broadsword?

463
00:55:41,255 --> 00:55:42,916
He's gone, sir.

464
00:55:44,049 --> 00:55:45,835
Damn it!

465
00:55:46,009 --> 00:55:48,091
It's all my fault.

466
00:55:48,262 --> 00:55:50,754
It's all our fault, colonel.

467
00:55:50,931 --> 00:55:53,013
It was my idea.

468
00:55:54,101 --> 00:55:56,308
Maybe I'm getting too old.

469
00:55:56,478 --> 00:55:58,765
Maybe we're both too old.

470
00:55:59,898 --> 00:56:02,686
Well, anyway, there can't be
any doubt anymore.

471
00:56:02,860 --> 00:56:06,649
The Germans have totally penetrated MI6.

472
00:56:07,197 --> 00:56:09,734
They know every move we make
almost before we make it.

473
00:56:09,908 --> 00:56:12,115
Where the hell are they
getting it all from?

474
00:56:12,286 --> 00:56:14,493
We handpicked every man
for this mission.

475
00:56:14,663 --> 00:56:17,781
- We have top security.
-Security?

476
00:56:18,792 --> 00:56:20,624
That word has become a bloody joke.

477
00:56:29,970 --> 00:56:31,961
[VEHICLE APPROACHING]

478
00:56:39,313 --> 00:56:41,304
[MEN SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

479
00:56:46,278 --> 00:56:48,144
We've got company.

480
00:57:00,584 --> 00:57:03,827
- Open the window.
-All right.

481
00:58:45,439 --> 00:58:47,430
[MEN SHOUTING IN GERMAN]

482
01:00:32,003 --> 01:00:33,960
[LAUGHING]

483
01:03:05,699 --> 01:03:10,489
Put the bag in the bus
and see if you can start the engine.

484
01:03:18,586 --> 01:03:20,577
[VEHICLE APPROACHING]

485
01:03:49,034 --> 01:03:50,900
- How's it going?
-Try to give it a start.

486
01:03:51,077 --> 01:03:52,613
Right.

487
01:05:24,254 --> 01:05:26,666
Yes. Captain Mueller,
with three prisoners.

488
01:05:27,173 --> 01:05:28,789
All right.

489
01:10:01,781 --> 01:10:03,271
[GRUNTING]

490
01:12:21,629 --> 01:12:25,042
Leave this one behind and
tie that one to the end of the rope.

491
01:13:00,668 --> 01:13:02,659
[MEN LAUGHING AND
SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

492
01:13:29,488 --> 01:13:31,525
Good God, that nearly killed me.

493
01:13:31,699 --> 01:13:34,157
You shouldn't go
on these insane missions.

494
01:13:34,327 --> 01:13:35,817
You're getting too old.

495
01:13:35,995 --> 01:13:39,613
I thank you for those few kind words.

496
01:13:40,708 --> 01:13:45,168
The first time I've been hot
since I was in this bloody country.

497
01:13:46,130 --> 01:13:48,337
- You got a plan of the castle?
-Yes.

498
01:13:48,507 --> 01:13:50,089
Well, fetch it for me, would you?

499
01:14:12,156 --> 01:14:14,693
Why don't you give him a hand?

500
01:14:15,117 --> 01:14:18,485
What for? He's perfectly capable
of looking after himself.

501
01:14:18,829 --> 01:14:20,911
If I could climb up on my own,
why can't he?

502
01:14:27,213 --> 01:14:29,671
First left down the stairs, third door.

503
01:14:29,840 --> 01:14:32,081
Next right-hander takes us
into the east wing.

504
01:14:32,385 --> 01:14:35,377
Down again. Second left.

505
01:14:35,554 --> 01:14:37,136
Telephone exchange.

506
01:14:37,640 --> 01:14:39,631
[SCHAFFER GRUNTING]

507
01:14:43,646 --> 01:14:47,640
You wouldn't mind giving me a hand,
would you?

508
01:14:54,490 --> 01:14:58,734
You seem to have a lot of women
stashed around this country, major.

509
01:14:58,911 --> 01:15:01,118
I'm sorry. This is Mary.
She's one of our group.

510
01:15:01,288 --> 01:15:03,370
- Lieutenant Schaffer.
-Hello.

511
01:15:04,959 --> 01:15:06,950
Hello, Mary.

512
01:15:43,497 --> 01:15:45,079
SMITH:
Thank you.

513
01:15:45,249 --> 01:15:47,616
Take the rope and the explosives
to your room...

514
01:15:47,793 --> 01:15:49,909
...and bring them with you
when you come.

515
01:16:29,835 --> 01:16:33,703
- How's it looking?
-it's quiet enough.

516
01:16:34,757 --> 01:16:37,089
First thing we gotta do
is cripple that helicopter.

517
01:16:37,259 --> 01:16:39,421
They might try to fly Carnaby out in it.

518
01:16:39,595 --> 01:16:41,802
I think we can handle that.

519
01:17:12,086 --> 01:17:13,668
Hello?

520
01:17:15,381 --> 01:17:17,372
[GRUNTING]

521
01:17:38,571 --> 01:17:40,733
- You the pilot?
PILOT: Yes, sir.

522
01:17:40,906 --> 01:17:43,022
Kommandant wants you on the phone.

523
01:17:43,200 --> 01:17:46,568
It's in the radio office on the left,
around the corner.

524
01:17:47,329 --> 01:17:51,072
- Do you have a cigarette, lieutenant?
-Yes, sir. Of course.

525
01:17:52,668 --> 01:17:54,955
- Rather cold, isn't it'?
-Oh, yes, sir.

526
01:18:32,791 --> 01:18:34,281
Well, that was quick.

527
01:18:34,501 --> 01:18:36,868
Fear lent them wings, as the saying goes.

528
01:18:37,046 --> 01:18:38,161
What do we do now?

529
01:18:38,339 --> 01:18:42,378
I think we'd better see how
Cartwright Jones is getting along.

530
01:19:10,663 --> 01:19:12,654
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

531
01:19:14,333 --> 01:19:17,826
KRAMER: You are making things
very difficult, Herr General.

532
01:19:18,003 --> 01:19:21,997
- Very, very difficult, indeed.
MAN: There aren't any difficulties, major.

533
01:19:22,174 --> 01:19:25,462
General Rosemeyer here hasn't forgotten
that Germany's a signatory...

534
01:19:25,636 --> 01:19:27,343
...to the Hague Convention.

535
01:19:27,513 --> 01:19:30,676
ROSEMEYER: I have not forgotten,
but my hands are tied.

536
01:19:30,849 --> 01:19:33,011
I have my orders from Berlin.

537
01:19:33,185 --> 01:19:35,472
MAN: You can tell Berlin
all they're entitled to know.

538
01:19:35,646 --> 01:19:41,107
I'm General George Carnaby,
United States Army, RA 123-025-3964.

539
01:19:41,277 --> 01:19:45,771
KRAMER: And one of the chief coordinators
of planning for the second front.

540
01:19:46,198 --> 01:19:48,405
JONES:
Which second front is that?

541
01:19:49,159 --> 01:19:52,322
Well, general, I have done all I can.

542
01:19:52,496 --> 01:19:55,363
I have tried to hold up the Gestapo.

543
01:19:55,541 --> 01:19:58,829
I've persuaded the High Command
that the mere fact of your capture...

544
01:19:59,003 --> 01:20:02,746
...will compel the Allies
to alter their plans...

545
01:20:03,007 --> 01:20:05,590
...but this, it seems, is not enough.

546
01:20:05,759 --> 01:20:09,218
For the last time, may I request you
to give us the information?

547
01:20:09,388 --> 01:20:13,347
General George Carnaby,
United States Army.

548
01:20:16,729 --> 01:20:19,391
The matter is in your hands, Kramer.

549
01:20:20,566 --> 01:20:23,729
You know, general,
we have drugs that will make you talk.

550
01:20:23,902 --> 01:20:27,566
- We do not wish to use them, but--
-Scopolamine. Heh, heh, heh.

551
01:20:27,740 --> 01:20:29,572
Where's that gonna get you, colonel?

552
01:20:29,742 --> 01:20:31,983
There are other drugs too.

553
01:20:32,161 --> 01:20:35,620
The lieutenant here is a trained nurse.

554
01:20:35,789 --> 01:20:37,621
[PHONE RINGS]

555
01:20:37,791 --> 01:20:39,657
Excuse me.

556
01:20:40,044 --> 01:20:41,250
Yes?

557
01:20:44,173 --> 01:20:46,585
And they are who we thought?

558
01:20:46,759 --> 01:20:48,420
Very good.

559
01:20:49,219 --> 01:20:51,802
Yes. Yes, you can bring them up now.

560
01:20:52,848 --> 01:20:56,136
Has there been any further information
about the other two?

561
01:20:57,895 --> 01:20:59,761
Well, keep me advised.

562
01:21:03,942 --> 01:21:07,560
Some very interesting company
coming up, general.

563
01:21:07,946 --> 01:21:10,563
The drugs may not be necessary.

564
01:21:13,243 --> 01:21:15,780
Don't you think
it's time we make a move?

565
01:21:17,122 --> 01:21:18,863
Any minute now.

566
01:21:19,041 --> 01:21:21,157
Just be patient.

567
01:21:48,654 --> 01:21:49,985
[KNOCKING]

568
01:21:50,656 --> 01:21:52,613
A moment.

569
01:22:01,959 --> 01:22:03,324
[MARY CHUCKLES]

570
01:22:03,502 --> 01:22:05,163
Fréulein.

571
01:22:06,338 --> 01:22:07,920
Did I disturb you?

572
01:22:08,090 --> 01:22:10,923
- No, I was just going out.
-Well, then I am just in time.

573
01:22:11,427 --> 01:22:14,670
- You wanted to see me, major?
-Naturally.

574
01:22:15,305 --> 01:22:16,636
What about?

575
01:22:19,351 --> 01:22:20,341
Well, nothing.

576
01:22:20,519 --> 01:22:24,638
I just wanted to see you.
Now, that is not a crime, is it?

577
01:22:25,065 --> 01:22:26,100
No.

578
01:22:26,275 --> 01:22:29,939
It's very seldom
we have so pretty a girl here.

579
01:22:30,362 --> 01:22:34,606
Perhaps I can show you
a little Bavarian hospitality.

580
01:22:35,033 --> 01:22:37,525
Now, downstairs,
we have an armaments room...

581
01:22:37,703 --> 01:22:41,071
...which has been converted
into the most marvelous cafe.

582
01:22:41,248 --> 01:22:44,240
But my duties,
I have to see the colonel's secretary.

583
01:22:44,418 --> 01:22:46,750
The colonel's secretary
can wait a little while.

584
01:22:46,920 --> 01:22:49,036
You and me, we have a lot to talk about.

585
01:22:49,214 --> 01:22:52,548
- Such as?
-Di]sseldorf.

586
01:22:53,218 --> 01:22:55,801
- D1'Jsseldorf?
-I was a student there for many years.

587
01:22:55,971 --> 01:22:59,384
From 1929 to 1933.

588
01:22:59,558 --> 01:23:01,674
To your health, gentlemen.

589
01:23:06,398 --> 01:23:08,139
You are not drinking, general.

590
01:23:10,360 --> 01:23:11,725
That's understandable...

591
01:23:12,237 --> 01:23:16,822
...when your rescuers turn out to be,
well, birds of a different feather.

592
01:23:18,452 --> 01:23:19,908
And the return trip, gentlemen.

593
01:23:20,537 --> 01:23:22,528
How was that to be accomplished?

594
01:23:22,706 --> 01:23:24,413
- Through Switzerland.
-Mm-hm.

595
01:23:24,583 --> 01:23:27,416
Then it should be quite easy
for you to return to London.

596
01:23:27,586 --> 01:23:30,544
A rubber dinghy across the Rhine,
and then a short walk.

597
01:23:30,714 --> 01:23:31,875
You'll be in Whitehall...

598
01:23:32,049 --> 01:23:35,258
...reporting General Carnaby's
transfer to Berlin before you know it.

599
01:23:35,427 --> 01:23:40,388
Back to London? Are you mad?
Not with Smith and Schaffer still alive.

600
01:23:40,891 --> 01:23:42,928
What do you take us for?

601
01:23:43,101 --> 01:23:47,265
You will also, of course, be reporting
the unfortunate demise of Major Smith.

602
01:23:48,899 --> 01:23:51,607
- Is he dead?
KRAMER: We are not quite sure.

603
01:23:52,027 --> 01:23:54,815
- It is being looked into right now.
-it's getting late.

604
01:23:54,988 --> 01:23:58,822
- Please remember the important issue.
-Yes, sir.

605
01:23:59,493 --> 01:24:01,951
I think the situation
has changed sufficiently...

606
01:24:02,120 --> 01:24:05,283
...for you to give us the information
we have been asking for.

607
01:24:05,457 --> 01:24:07,949
Nothing's changed, colonel.

608
01:24:09,378 --> 01:24:11,961
Most unfortunate.

609
01:24:39,491 --> 01:24:43,075
Just a waste of good scopolamine.
Don't move, any of you.

610
01:24:43,579 --> 01:24:45,240
Lieutenant.

611
01:24:45,414 --> 01:24:48,827
No, I'd advise you not to, colonel.

612
01:24:50,502 --> 01:24:54,245
Well, gentlemen, I'm glad to see you all
here, safe and sound, enjoying a drink.

613
01:24:54,423 --> 01:24:57,290
I'm sorry to interrupt you.

614
01:24:57,467 --> 01:24:59,504
Lieutenant, drop that gun.

615
01:25:00,596 --> 01:25:03,008
- What?
-Drop that gun and sit down.

616
01:25:06,685 --> 01:25:09,518
- What the hell are you talking about?
-Sit down!

617
01:25:19,031 --> 01:25:22,865
- Major, if I live to be 100--
-Do nothing, lieutenant.

618
01:25:23,952 --> 01:25:25,534
[GUN CLATTERS]

619
01:25:25,996 --> 01:25:28,363
In your own idiom, you're a punk...

620
01:25:29,374 --> 01:25:31,866
...and a pretty second-rate punk at that.

621
01:25:32,044 --> 01:25:37,255
- If I might have some explanation...
-In good time, colonel. All in good time.

622
01:25:37,424 --> 01:25:40,758
I was about to say scopolamine
would have little effect on our friend...

623
01:25:40,927 --> 01:25:45,012
...except to prove he's not General Carnaby,
but a certain Cartwright Jones...

624
01:25:45,182 --> 01:25:47,514
...an American actor
impersonating General Carnaby.

625
01:25:47,684 --> 01:25:50,642
- Who are you?
-Just a passer-by, as you might say.

626
01:25:50,812 --> 01:25:53,395
In fact, I think the drug
would probably work better...

627
01:25:53,565 --> 01:25:56,853
...on our friends at the end of the table.
They're our real enemies.

628
01:25:57,027 --> 01:25:59,860
- Don't listen to him, general. It's a bluff!
-Keep quiet!

629
01:26:03,200 --> 01:26:06,864
Allow me to introduce myself.
Major Johann Schmidt.

630
01:26:07,037 --> 01:26:10,075
SS Military Intelligence, Stuttgart.

631
01:26:10,248 --> 01:26:12,330
- Can you prove that?
-Certainly, colonel.

632
01:26:12,501 --> 01:26:15,914
Before I do, I wonder if you'd be
good enough to call one of your guards.

633
01:26:16,088 --> 01:26:20,582
I don't fancy talking and keeping my eye
on these people at the same time.

634
01:26:23,053 --> 01:26:24,964
Strange.

635
01:26:26,890 --> 01:26:29,427
I seem to remember...

636
01:26:29,601 --> 01:26:32,810
...that the cathedral was
on the other side of the square.

637
01:26:35,774 --> 01:26:37,515
Well...

638
01:26:38,860 --> 01:26:41,773
Of course, I might be mistaken.
It's been a long time.

639
01:26:43,198 --> 01:26:46,407
Oh, no, major.
I could have made a mistake.

640
01:26:46,576 --> 01:26:49,910
I haven't been to Dilsseldorf
for three years.

641
01:26:50,372 --> 01:26:52,238
It's very easy to forget.

642
01:26:52,416 --> 01:26:55,499
Yes. It's very easy.

643
01:26:59,965 --> 01:27:03,128
Fréulein, you seem to be
a little bit distracted.

644
01:27:04,386 --> 01:27:06,844
- Is anything wrong?
-No. No, it's nothing.

645
01:27:07,013 --> 01:27:10,802
Just a slight headache.
I've had a long day traveling.

646
01:27:11,810 --> 01:27:14,302
Oh, yes, of course. And here I am...

647
01:27:14,479 --> 01:27:18,438
...I'm talking about silly things
like Dusseldorf.

648
01:27:19,317 --> 01:27:21,479
- You will forgive me?
-Of course.

649
01:27:21,653 --> 01:27:23,143
Thank you. I tell you what.

650
01:27:23,321 --> 01:27:27,815
We will have one more schnapps together
and then I'll see you to your quarters.

651
01:27:27,993 --> 01:27:29,483
- Thank you.
-Fréulein!

652
01:27:34,833 --> 01:27:38,167
Well, now that we're all comfortable,
the first order of business...

653
01:27:38,336 --> 01:27:42,375
...is to find out exactly who everybody is
and what they're doing here.

654
01:27:42,632 --> 01:27:44,999
Now, first the lieutenant.

655
01:27:45,177 --> 01:27:46,667
He's an assassin...

656
01:27:46,845 --> 01:27:51,260
...a member of the American
intelligence organization known as OSS.

657
01:27:51,433 --> 01:27:55,552
His job was to shoot you, Colonel Kramer,
and you, General Rosemeyer.

658
01:27:55,729 --> 01:27:59,188
Now, General Carnaby's mission
was twofold:

659
01:27:59,357 --> 01:28:01,223
First, to allow himself to be tortured...

660
01:28:01,401 --> 01:28:03,984
...into giving you the wrong plans
for the second front.

661
01:28:04,154 --> 01:28:05,986
And secondly, to afford the British...

662
01:28:06,156 --> 01:28:09,319
...a perfect excuse to send in
a team of experts to rescue him.

663
01:28:09,493 --> 01:28:12,281
Which brings us
to our three friends here...

664
01:28:12,454 --> 01:28:14,866
...and the cleverest phase
of the British operation.

665
01:28:15,040 --> 01:28:17,407
- They are, of course, members of MI6.
-That's a lie.

666
01:28:17,584 --> 01:28:19,541
Let him finish!

667
01:28:19,711 --> 01:28:22,544
Their job was to penetrate
the German High Command...

668
01:28:22,714 --> 01:28:26,548
...instead of the real
Thomas, Berkeley and Christiansen...

669
01:28:26,718 --> 01:28:28,675
...who worked for us in London...

670
01:28:28,845 --> 01:28:32,463
...and were discovered and captured
by the British about a month ago.

671
01:28:32,641 --> 01:28:34,848
That's another lie.
You can't prove any of this.

672
01:28:35,018 --> 01:28:36,600
Can't I?

673
01:28:37,229 --> 01:28:39,721
Any denials, lieutenant?

674
01:28:43,235 --> 01:28:46,398
Now, General Carnaby,
perhaps you'd be good enough...

675
01:28:46,571 --> 01:28:49,689
...to give us your real name, rank
and serial number.

676
01:29:00,168 --> 01:29:02,626
Cartwright Jones, corporal, U.S. Army...

677
01:29:02,921 --> 01:29:06,789
...RA 123-025-3964.

678
01:29:06,967 --> 01:29:08,583
SCHMIDT:
Thank you.

679
01:29:09,010 --> 01:29:12,753
Having successfully substituted
these three British agents for our men...

680
01:29:12,931 --> 01:29:15,343
...what was the next phase
of the British plan?

681
01:29:15,517 --> 01:29:17,929
To penetrate the German High Command.

682
01:29:18,103 --> 01:29:20,390
How? Simple.

683
01:29:20,564 --> 01:29:24,728
Stage a fake air crash
with a fake American general on board...

684
01:29:24,901 --> 01:29:27,438
...send in special agents
to effect his release...

685
01:29:27,612 --> 01:29:29,728
...be sure that they fail in their mission...

686
01:29:29,906 --> 01:29:32,113
...and these men
would be taken to Berlin...

687
01:29:32,284 --> 01:29:35,117
...where they would be
right in the heart of the Wehrmacht.

688
01:29:35,287 --> 01:29:38,780
And you, Major Schmidt,
what were your orders on this mission?

689
01:29:39,457 --> 01:29:42,245
To lead them in and make
my own way out through Switzerland.

690
01:29:42,919 --> 01:29:46,878
- But it-- It's incredible.
-Yes.

691
01:29:47,048 --> 01:29:49,289
But to the British, very, very simple.

692
01:29:49,843 --> 01:29:52,631
You were going to give us
some proof of who you are.

693
01:29:52,804 --> 01:29:54,636
SCHMIDT:
Certainly, general.

694
01:29:54,848 --> 01:29:58,136
The proof is in three parts.
First, if I'm not who I say I am...

695
01:29:58,310 --> 01:30:01,553
...what am I doing here?
What can I possibly hope to gain?

696
01:30:01,730 --> 01:30:05,815
The rescue of an impostor,
the exposure of three spies. Who to?

697
01:30:05,984 --> 01:30:08,646
To the very people
they're supposed to be working for.

698
01:30:08,820 --> 01:30:11,107
I have nothing to gain.

699
01:30:11,531 --> 01:30:15,274
Also, if these people
are what they say they are...

700
01:30:15,452 --> 01:30:19,161
...they would know the name
of our top agent in Whitehall.

701
01:30:19,331 --> 01:30:21,618
- Yes.
-So why don't we ask them?

702
01:30:26,838 --> 01:30:29,546
They should know the man
who sent them on this mission.

703
01:30:29,716 --> 01:30:31,832
CHRISTIANSEN:
We all work through contacts.

704
01:30:32,010 --> 01:30:34,217
It wasn't necessary
or safe for us to know...

705
01:30:34,387 --> 01:30:36,298
...where our orders were coming from.

706
01:30:36,473 --> 01:30:40,512
Then I should be in the same boat as you,
but I know his name and you don't.

707
01:30:43,813 --> 01:30:45,178
Secondly, colonel, you have...

708
01:30:45,357 --> 01:30:48,145
...one of the most powerful
radio transmitters in Europe.

709
01:30:48,318 --> 01:30:51,026
Put a radio telephone call through...

710
01:30:51,196 --> 01:30:53,858
...to Field Marshal Kesselring's
headquarters in Italy...

711
01:30:54,032 --> 01:30:58,572
...and ask for his Chief of Intelligence,
a Major Wilhelm Wilner.

712
01:31:06,878 --> 01:31:09,040
Major. Major.

713
01:31:09,214 --> 01:31:10,579
Major.

714
01:31:10,757 --> 01:31:15,752
There's Colonel Kramer on the telephone
from the Schloss Adler in Bavaria.

715
01:31:16,346 --> 01:31:18,462
He says it's very urgent.

716
01:31:18,682 --> 01:31:19,717
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

717
01:31:19,891 --> 01:31:21,723
Major Wilner speaking.

718
01:31:22,644 --> 01:31:23,725
Ja, colonel.

719
01:31:23,895 --> 01:31:27,388
- Can you describe him?
-That will not be necessary.

720
01:31:27,565 --> 01:31:29,556
Ask him to show you his right forearm.

721
01:31:30,402 --> 01:31:34,066
- May I see your right forearm?
-Certainly.

722
01:31:35,198 --> 01:31:39,863
WILNER [OVER <i>PHONE]: There are two
parallel scars, about three centimeters apart.</i>

723
01:31:40,036 --> 01:31:41,276
The scars are there.

724
01:31:42,080 --> 01:31:43,741
Ask how did he get them.

725
01:31:44,332 --> 01:31:46,539
- How did you get those?
-I was born with them.

726
01:31:46,710 --> 01:31:48,075
KRAMER:
He says he was born with them.

727
01:31:48,461 --> 01:31:51,294
That is right. Then tell him he's a traitor.

728
01:31:51,631 --> 01:31:52,792
Tell him he's a renegade.

729
01:31:53,008 --> 01:31:54,419
[LAUGHING]

730
01:31:54,592 --> 01:31:57,004
That is Schmidt. No question about it.

731
01:31:58,221 --> 01:32:01,304
- Thank you, major.
-Thank you, colonel.

732
01:32:01,474 --> 01:32:03,431
Good night.

733
01:32:04,352 --> 01:32:06,468
Give me the water.

734
01:32:10,775 --> 01:32:13,767
As you know, the real Thomas,
Christiansen and Berkeley...

735
01:32:13,945 --> 01:32:16,687
...while working
for British counterespionage...

736
01:32:16,865 --> 01:32:21,359
...were responsible for setting up an
excellent chain of agents throughout Britain.

737
01:32:21,536 --> 01:32:24,244
Now, if these men are
who they claim to be...

738
01:32:24,414 --> 01:32:25,904
...it would be reasonable...

739
01:32:26,082 --> 01:32:29,291
...to expect them to be able
to write down a list of those agents.

740
01:32:29,461 --> 01:32:32,749
You could then compare their lists
with the genuine one...

741
01:32:32,922 --> 01:32:36,131
...which I have in this book.
-There's something very wrong, colonel.

742
01:32:36,301 --> 01:32:40,044
I don't doubt who Schmidt is,
but there has been some mistake.

743
01:32:40,221 --> 01:32:43,339
SCHMIDT: Yes, and you're the ones
who have made it.

744
01:32:43,516 --> 01:32:47,635
Fréiulein, would you be good enough
to get some pencils and some notebooks...

745
01:32:47,812 --> 01:32:51,350
...and we'll soon find out
who's speaking the truth.

746
01:32:54,069 --> 01:32:57,528
Good night, Maria.
You are a most charming girl.

747
01:32:57,697 --> 01:32:58,983
Good night and thank you.

748
01:32:59,157 --> 01:33:01,273
We must get to know each other
a little better.

749
01:33:01,451 --> 01:33:02,862
- Yes.
-Good night.

750
01:33:03,036 --> 01:33:04,652
Good night.

751
01:33:57,340 --> 01:33:59,422
Any one of these will do.

752
01:34:29,747 --> 01:34:32,330
Now compare it with my original.

753
01:34:47,682 --> 01:34:48,888
Guard!

754
01:34:49,142 --> 01:34:50,428
[GRUNTS]

755
01:34:52,687 --> 01:34:54,098
Stay as you were, gentlemen.

756
01:34:55,315 --> 01:34:56,476
Just relax.

757
01:35:01,946 --> 01:35:03,277
Second-rate punk, huh?

758
01:35:04,407 --> 01:35:06,569
All I could think of
on the spur of the moment.

759
01:35:06,743 --> 01:35:10,281
- Thanks. That even makes it worse.
-Sorry.

760
01:35:10,955 --> 01:35:13,947
Well, between them,
they shouldn't have missed anything.

761
01:35:14,125 --> 01:35:17,709
KRAMER: This is all you want. Those books?
-Lots of nice names and addresses.

762
01:35:19,297 --> 01:35:22,790
And these men?
Then they are who they claim to be?

763
01:35:23,718 --> 01:35:26,927
I'm afraid so. They've been
under suspicion for some time.

764
01:35:27,096 --> 01:35:31,135
Classified information was going out
and useless information was coming in.

765
01:35:31,309 --> 01:35:34,927
It took several weeks to pin it on
the departments controlled by those men.

766
01:35:35,104 --> 01:35:37,516
But we knew we couldn't prove it.
Even if we could...

767
01:35:37,690 --> 01:35:40,307
...what we really wanted
was the names of their contacts.

768
01:35:40,485 --> 01:35:43,819
These names and addresses.
So we thought this plan up.

769
01:35:43,988 --> 01:35:46,320
And Wilner,
Kesselring's Chief of Intelligence?

770
01:35:46,491 --> 01:35:49,153
He truly believes me
to be one of his top agents in Italy.

771
01:35:49,327 --> 01:35:53,241
I've been feeding him useless, false and
out-of-date information for a couple years.

772
01:35:53,414 --> 01:35:55,155
- All right, gentlemen--
VON HAPEN: Stay where you are!

773
01:35:55,500 --> 01:35:56,661
[GUN COCKS]

774
01:35:58,878 --> 01:36:02,963
I'd advise everyone to keep perfectly still.

775
01:36:04,842 --> 01:36:07,049
Drop your gun, major.

776
01:36:09,180 --> 01:36:11,262
You too, lieutenant.

777
01:36:19,148 --> 01:36:20,263
By the fireplace.

778
01:36:23,861 --> 01:36:25,852
Thank God you're here.
We were just about--

779
01:36:26,030 --> 01:36:28,738
VON HAPEN:
Sit down, colonel!

780
01:36:34,914 --> 01:36:38,282
Everybody remain as he is...

781
01:36:39,585 --> 01:36:43,419
...until I find out
what exactly is going on here.

782
01:36:43,589 --> 01:36:45,796
What do you mean?
Surely, you can see what's--

783
01:36:45,967 --> 01:36:49,460
VON HAPEN:
Sit down, colonel.

784
01:36:49,637 --> 01:36:52,379
It's perfectly simple.
The lieutenant and myself...

785
01:36:52,557 --> 01:36:54,969
...have uncovered a plot
to assassinate the Fuhrer.

786
01:36:55,268 --> 01:36:58,260
- This is preposterous!
-General!

787
01:36:59,063 --> 01:37:00,098
Sit down.

788
01:37:03,276 --> 01:37:06,940
These people were all involved in
a conspiracy to overthrow the Third Reich.

789
01:37:07,113 --> 01:37:09,901
In my pocket here,
I have the names of all the conspirators.

790
01:37:10,074 --> 01:37:13,283
Just before you interrupted us,
we put this entire party under arrest.

791
01:37:13,578 --> 01:37:17,071
The list in his pocket are the names
of German agents working in Britain!

792
01:37:17,415 --> 01:37:19,247
SMITH:
I don't expect you to believe me, major.

793
01:37:19,876 --> 01:37:24,120
But you'll certainly believe these names
if you'll permit me to show them to you.

794
01:37:27,383 --> 01:37:29,340
Let me see them.

795
01:37:31,804 --> 01:37:34,216
Careful, major.

796
01:37:35,933 --> 01:37:37,719
Go very slowly.

797
01:37:52,909 --> 01:37:54,650
Bring them here.

798
01:37:59,123 --> 01:38:00,659
Bring them here.

799
01:38:01,501 --> 01:38:02,957
SCHAFFER:
Smith.

800
01:38:06,464 --> 01:38:07,625
[KRAMER GRUNTS]

801
01:38:15,473 --> 01:38:18,807
All of you, get up! Stand over there.

802
01:38:19,185 --> 01:38:20,892
Put your hands up.

803
01:38:22,021 --> 01:38:23,978
Put your hands up!

804
01:38:24,816 --> 01:38:27,649
Jones, see if you can find
something to tie them up with.

805
01:38:27,819 --> 01:38:29,901
Mary, bring that bag over here.

806
01:38:32,824 --> 01:38:35,407
- What do we do with these three?
-We take them with us.

807
01:38:35,576 --> 01:38:36,611
You were late.

808
01:38:36,786 --> 01:38:39,619
- One day I won't come at all.
-Keep your eye on those three.

809
01:38:39,789 --> 01:38:41,496
Lieutenant, in the next 15 minutes...

810
01:38:41,666 --> 01:38:44,658
...we have to create enough confusion
to get out of here alive.

811
01:38:44,836 --> 01:38:48,420
Major, right now you got me
about as confused as I ever hope to be.

812
01:38:48,589 --> 01:38:51,377
The armory's here.
if we blow it up, the castle will think...

813
01:38:51,551 --> 01:38:53,337
...it's being attacked by a division.

814
01:38:53,553 --> 01:38:56,341
On the other side of the castle over here
is the radio room.

815
01:38:56,514 --> 01:38:59,632
I'll take the others and meet you there.
You take the map.

816
01:39:08,401 --> 01:39:10,688
Mary, we're going.

817
01:39:12,613 --> 01:39:15,526
Let me make myself
perfectly understood.

818
01:39:15,700 --> 01:39:20,695
If any of you utters a word, I'll kill you all.
You understand?

819
01:39:20,872 --> 01:39:23,455
- Jones, get the major's gun. Now move.
-Yes, sir.

820
01:39:23,624 --> 01:39:24,955
Move!

821
01:39:25,126 --> 01:39:26,662
Go!

822
01:39:55,615 --> 01:39:57,276
This way.

823
01:40:19,388 --> 01:40:21,095
Jones.

824
01:42:04,118 --> 01:42:05,199
[MAN 1 SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

825
01:42:05,369 --> 01:42:09,408
SMITH: Wait. Go back. Jones, go on.
Mary, get in. Get in there.

826
01:42:10,750 --> 01:42:12,741
[MAN 2 LAUGHING AND SPEAKING
IN GERMAN]

827
01:42:38,444 --> 01:42:40,355
At ease.

828
01:42:43,866 --> 01:42:45,573
Hello.

829
01:42:47,244 --> 01:42:48,234
[MAN GRUNTS]

830
01:42:48,412 --> 01:42:49,743
[GUNSHOTS AND GUARD GRUNTS]

831
01:43:21,445 --> 01:43:23,436
[CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS]

832
01:44:00,943 --> 01:44:02,934
[POLKA MUSIC PLAYING]

833
01:44:32,308 --> 01:44:33,343
[WHISPERING]
Get them in.

834
01:44:54,121 --> 01:44:56,112
[CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO]

835
01:46:11,782 --> 01:46:14,114
[STATIC BUZZING ON RADIO]

836
01:46:17,162 --> 01:46:19,153
[POLKA MUSIC PLAYING]

837
01:46:26,463 --> 01:46:27,794
[FLOOR CREAKS]

838
01:46:29,466 --> 01:46:31,457
[ALARM RINGING]

839
01:46:36,557 --> 01:46:38,548
[SIRENS WAILING]

840
01:46:54,283 --> 01:46:56,775
[IN NORMAL TONE]
All right, inside, quickly.

841
01:47:03,667 --> 01:47:05,533
You may need this.

842
01:47:31,362 --> 01:47:33,148
Broadsword calling Danny Boy.

843
01:47:33,697 --> 01:47:35,358
Broadsword calling Danny Boy.

844
01:47:42,414 --> 01:47:45,702
- We got company.
-Broadsword calling Danny Boy.

845
01:48:20,411 --> 01:48:22,618
Broadsword calling Danny Boy.

846
01:49:16,842 --> 01:49:18,799
Broadsword calling Danny Boy.

847
01:49:18,969 --> 01:49:20,050
[EXPLOSIONS IN DISTANCE]

848
01:49:20,220 --> 01:49:21,255
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

849
01:49:24,016 --> 01:49:26,007
[RUMBLING AND EXPLOSIONS
IN DISTANCE]

850
01:49:27,436 --> 01:49:31,350
Get the rest of the men out of here
and report to the Kommandant.

851
01:49:32,733 --> 01:49:33,814
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

852
01:49:42,326 --> 01:49:45,364
<i>ROLLAND</i> [OVER <i>RADIO]: <i>
Danny Boy calling Broadsword. Over.</i>

853
01:49:45,537 --> 01:49:48,620
Everything ready.
We need transport. Understood?

854
01:49:48,791 --> 01:49:50,828
- Over.
-Understood.

855
01:49:51,001 --> 01:49:53,493
Do you have it? Over.

856
01:49:53,670 --> 01:49:56,662
<i>We have it. We have it all. Over.</i>

857
01:49:56,840 --> 01:49:58,205
All sins forgiven.

858
01:50:00,385 --> 01:50:02,376
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

859
01:50:05,349 --> 01:50:07,090
Damn it.

860
01:50:09,019 --> 01:50:11,010
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

861
01:50:16,151 --> 01:50:18,142
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

862
01:50:21,949 --> 01:50:24,657
Get Thomas out of there. Quickly.

863
01:50:30,707 --> 01:50:32,698
[EXPLOSION]

864
01:50:34,503 --> 01:50:35,789
NQW!

865
01:50:50,102 --> 01:50:52,594
Get out. Climb out.

866
01:50:52,771 --> 01:50:54,136
Get on with it!

867
01:51:05,868 --> 01:51:07,529
Grenades.

868
01:51:40,194 --> 01:51:41,935
Corporal!

869
01:51:44,156 --> 01:51:46,147
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

870
01:51:47,034 --> 01:51:49,025
[GRUNTING]

871
01:51:59,087 --> 01:52:01,078
[EXPLOSION]

872
01:52:02,216 --> 01:52:05,550
Outside! Out! Out!

873
01:52:09,806 --> 01:52:11,797
[EXPLOSION]

874
01:52:39,127 --> 01:52:40,743
SMITH:
All right.

875
01:52:41,672 --> 01:52:43,663
Lieutenant, get the rope.

876
01:53:14,663 --> 01:53:16,654
[FOOTSTEPS AND
MAN SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

877
01:53:17,791 --> 01:53:19,782
[WHISPERING]
Back. Get back.

878
01:53:39,229 --> 01:53:41,516
[IN NORMAL TONE]
All right, to the right.

879
01:54:19,644 --> 01:54:20,679
[MAN SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

880
01:54:20,854 --> 01:54:22,811
Quick. Move it.

881
01:54:27,986 --> 01:54:29,897
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

882
01:54:30,072 --> 01:54:32,439
Damn! Blast it!

883
01:54:33,700 --> 01:54:35,407
Get moving.

884
01:54:53,178 --> 01:54:55,545
All right. Get those men untied.

885
01:54:58,809 --> 01:55:03,303
Better put those coats on if you don't
want to freeze to death. Quickly, now.

886
01:56:14,384 --> 01:56:15,374
Christiansen.

887
01:57:02,057 --> 01:57:04,719
Jones, get them out. Mary.

888
01:57:44,391 --> 01:57:47,850
Watch them. Right.

889
01:58:47,996 --> 01:58:49,703
[EXPLOSIONS IN DISTANCE]

890
01:59:59,025 --> 02:00:03,440
- The doors to the corridor are locked.
-See what winch controls they have.

891
02:00:11,246 --> 02:00:15,490
- There's a stop and start button.
-See if you can make the motor work.

892
02:00:20,213 --> 02:00:22,454
SCHAFFER: Not bad, huh?
-Yes, good.

893
02:00:22,632 --> 02:00:26,626
Now bring it down here and we'll get
on top, and you can take us back inside.

894
02:00:32,225 --> 02:00:35,559
- Mary, bring them out here!
-Go on.

895
02:00:46,531 --> 02:00:48,943
Get ahold of the rope and climb down.

896
02:00:50,785 --> 02:00:52,651
Climb down!

897
02:01:23,693 --> 02:01:25,183
[GROANING]

898
02:01:29,157 --> 02:01:30,773
Look out!

899
02:01:30,950 --> 02:01:32,941
[GRUNTING]

900
02:01:43,546 --> 02:01:45,378
Schaffer?

901
02:01:46,591 --> 02:01:49,583
Schaffer? Schaffer?

902
02:01:49,844 --> 02:01:53,758
We've got him, Smith! Now, listen, Smith.

903
02:01:53,932 --> 02:01:55,548
I'll make a deal with you.

904
02:01:55,975 --> 02:02:00,640
You let us go down in the car
and we won't kill Schaffer.

905
02:02:03,733 --> 02:02:04,768
Smith!

906
02:02:04,943 --> 02:02:07,605
You bring him out
so I can see he's still alive.

907
02:02:10,365 --> 02:02:12,402
I'm bringing him out now.

908
02:02:12,700 --> 02:02:14,737
[WHISPERING]
Get in the car.

909
02:03:03,543 --> 02:03:05,534
[THUDS]

910
02:03:13,970 --> 02:03:15,756
[IN NORMAL TONE]
Give me that.

911
02:03:16,139 --> 02:03:17,470
[THUD]

912
02:03:21,477 --> 02:03:22,808
[GUN CLICKING]

913
02:03:26,024 --> 02:03:27,856
Damn it!

914
02:03:34,157 --> 02:03:36,740
Up there. Get him!

915
02:03:46,586 --> 02:03:48,577
[GRUNTING]

916
02:04:13,071 --> 02:04:14,402
[GROANING]

917
02:04:28,044 --> 02:04:29,705
[SCREAMS]

918
02:05:22,682 --> 02:05:25,140
Help me. No.

919
02:05:29,439 --> 02:05:32,101
No. No!

920
02:05:32,275 --> 02:05:34,266
[CHRISTIANSEN WHIMPERING]

921
02:05:34,944 --> 02:05:36,275
[CHRISTIANSEN SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

922
02:05:36,446 --> 02:05:38,437
Help me.

923
02:05:39,449 --> 02:05:41,440
[SCREAMING]

924
02:05:46,289 --> 02:05:47,279
Please.

925
02:05:57,133 --> 02:05:58,715
No!

926
02:05:58,885 --> 02:06:01,627
No!

927
02:08:20,776 --> 02:08:22,767
[BANGING ON DOOR IN DISTANCE]

928
02:08:28,784 --> 02:08:30,616
MARY:
Lieutenant.

929
02:08:34,123 --> 02:08:36,455
- Where's the major?
-He's on the cable car.

930
02:08:36,792 --> 02:08:38,783
[BANGING ON DOOR CONTINUES]

931
02:08:49,305 --> 02:08:51,296
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

932
02:09:45,695 --> 02:09:47,026
[OFFICER SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

933
02:10:04,380 --> 02:10:06,371
[BANGING ON DOOR]

934
02:10:15,850 --> 02:10:17,716
SMITH:
Jones, the bag.

935
02:10:33,701 --> 02:10:35,362
Let's go.

936
02:11:23,084 --> 02:11:25,075
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

937
02:11:49,276 --> 02:11:52,143
Set the bombs to go off
in three and a half minutes.

938
02:12:24,353 --> 02:12:26,720
- Almost ready?
-Almost.

939
02:12:27,648 --> 02:12:30,857
Jones. Mary.

940
02:12:38,617 --> 02:12:39,698
All set.

941
02:12:45,374 --> 02:12:46,705
Go.

942
02:13:46,268 --> 02:13:47,758
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

943
02:13:50,898 --> 02:13:52,229
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

944
02:14:29,103 --> 02:14:33,062
- Twenty-five minutes. Can we make it?
-We can make it.

945
02:14:33,232 --> 02:14:35,724
- Point is, will they?
-God knows.

946
02:15:07,057 --> 02:15:09,344
Everybody on the floor.

947
02:15:43,552 --> 02:15:44,792
[GRUNTING]

948
02:15:56,565 --> 02:15:57,726
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

949
02:16:00,694 --> 02:16:02,685
[ALARM WAILING]

950
02:16:10,079 --> 02:16:13,117
Emergency. Get me
the Oberhausen Airfield immediately.

951
02:16:52,287 --> 02:16:56,622
- We've got company.
-Yeah, I saw them in the mirror.

952
02:16:59,837 --> 02:17:02,454
How long before we reach the poles?

953
02:17:02,631 --> 02:17:04,622
Just around the next turn.

954
02:17:05,092 --> 02:17:07,254
Oberhausen Airfield?

955
02:17:08,387 --> 02:17:10,048
Give me the Kommandant's office.

956
02:18:03,192 --> 02:18:04,523
[PHONE CLICKING]

957
02:18:27,925 --> 02:18:29,916
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

958
02:19:34,283 --> 02:19:35,899
Get ready.

959
02:20:29,504 --> 02:20:30,619
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

960
02:21:01,370 --> 02:21:03,111
[MOTORCYCLE APPROACHING]

961
02:21:23,725 --> 02:21:25,716
Set the rest of them and get out of here.

962
02:21:59,928 --> 02:22:01,919
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

963
02:23:50,205 --> 02:23:54,199
PILOT: Oberhausen control tower.
Oberhausen control tower.

964
02:23:55,043 --> 02:23:56,659
MAN:
Oberhausen control. Over.

965
02:23:57,254 --> 02:24:01,794
PILOT: I'm in serious trouble.
Request urgent permission to land. Over.

966
02:24:02,926 --> 02:24:05,793
Identify. Over.

967
02:24:05,971 --> 02:24:07,086
ULRICH [OVER RADIO]:
Leutnant Ulrich.

968
02:24:07,556 --> 02:24:11,515
Third Jaeger Junker squadron
on night navigational exercise.

969
02:24:11,685 --> 02:24:14,393
One engine out. Losing altitude. Over.

970
02:24:15,272 --> 02:24:17,388
You are cleared
for immediate landing. Over.

971
02:24:17,566 --> 02:24:19,648
PILOT:
Coming in. Over.

972
02:24:32,706 --> 02:24:34,697
[AIRCRAFT APPROACHING]

973
02:25:25,300 --> 02:25:26,631
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

974
02:25:31,056 --> 02:25:33,138
[ALARM WAILING]

975
02:25:59,459 --> 02:26:02,997
Fighter Wing 126,
Oberhausen Airfield calling. Over.

976
02:26:03,505 --> 02:26:04,961
Fighter Wing 126, Ober--

977
02:26:05,966 --> 02:26:08,173
Get the control tower.

978
02:26:10,845 --> 02:26:12,256
Come in-- Aah!

979
02:27:26,504 --> 02:27:28,086
SMITH:
Get down.

980
02:27:46,149 --> 02:27:48,140
[RAPID GUNFIRE]

981
02:28:33,446 --> 02:28:37,030
- Berkeley wrote these names?
-Yes, sir.

982
02:28:38,993 --> 02:28:43,078
Ted Berkeley. I can't believe it.

983
02:28:43,248 --> 02:28:46,957
And Thomas. And Christiansen.

984
02:28:48,169 --> 02:28:50,001
All three of them?

985
02:28:52,132 --> 02:28:55,841
- My God, it's incredible.
-Yes, quite.

986
02:28:56,010 --> 02:29:01,005
But not as incredible as the one name
that's missing from that list, colonel.

987
02:29:02,684 --> 02:29:05,301
What name is that, major?

988
02:29:05,854 --> 02:29:09,313
I have it in this notebook
here in my pocket.

989
02:29:09,482 --> 02:29:12,270
Earlier tonight, I showed it
to Colonel Kramer.

990
02:29:12,444 --> 02:29:17,405
He agreed with me that this was
the top German agent in Britain.

991
02:29:30,211 --> 02:29:32,794
It's your name, colonel.
Don't look so shocked.

992
02:29:33,339 --> 02:29:35,797
Surely, you suspected it.

993
02:29:36,009 --> 02:29:38,046
Otherwise, why were you here
to meet us?

994
02:29:39,053 --> 02:29:40,589
In case you were found out?

995
02:29:43,892 --> 02:29:45,633
Go on.

996
02:29:47,061 --> 02:29:49,803
You see, you underestimated
Admiral Rolland.

997
02:29:49,981 --> 02:29:52,473
He'd suspected you and the others
for some time.

998
02:29:52,775 --> 02:29:56,063
He brought me and Mary back from Italy
because we were the only two...

999
02:29:56,237 --> 02:29:59,229
...in his department that he could trust,
yourself included.

1000
02:29:59,866 --> 02:30:02,528
He asked you to choose a leader
for this expedition.

1001
02:30:03,161 --> 02:30:05,823
You chose me because you knew
from German intelligence...

1002
02:30:05,997 --> 02:30:09,206
...that I was a double agent.

1003
02:30:09,834 --> 02:30:12,747
Admiral Rolland knew I was not.

1004
02:30:12,921 --> 02:30:15,754
But for you, I was the perfect choice.

1005
02:30:16,216 --> 02:30:20,710
- Now you're guessing, Smith.
-No guesswork, colonel.

1006
02:30:20,887 --> 02:30:24,881
Your pointing that gun at me
is sufficient evidence.

1007
02:30:28,269 --> 02:30:30,601
You are pointing it at me, aren't you?

1008
02:30:32,649 --> 02:30:33,889
Go on.

1009
02:30:34,067 --> 02:30:37,731
Mary was brought on the mission without
your knowledge because I needed her...

1010
02:30:37,904 --> 02:30:41,147
...to get me into the castle.
The lieutenant, being an American...

1011
02:30:41,324 --> 02:30:43,315
...had no possible connection with MI6...

1012
02:30:43,493 --> 02:30:46,030
...and was the only member of the group
I could trust.

1013
02:30:46,204 --> 02:30:48,787
I wasn't even sure of
Harrod and MacPherson...

1014
02:30:48,957 --> 02:30:50,573
...until they were killed by the others.

1015
02:30:53,211 --> 02:30:57,125
Fascinating. Very fascinating.

1016
02:30:57,298 --> 02:30:59,039
Perhaps even true.

1017
02:31:00,593 --> 02:31:03,676
- Assuming for a moment--
-You're finished, colonel.

1018
02:31:08,893 --> 02:31:14,138
- You're overlooking something, aren't you?
-Not at all.

1019
02:31:14,649 --> 02:31:17,562
Admiral Rolland took you
to the plane himself, didn't he?

1020
02:31:18,152 --> 02:31:22,237
He also made certain
that you had that gun, didn't he?

1021
02:31:22,949 --> 02:31:27,364
We took the precaution of removing
the firing pin before the mission started.

1022
02:31:33,334 --> 02:31:34,665
[GUN CLICKS]

1023
02:31:36,296 --> 02:31:37,752
Put it down, colonel.

1024
02:31:41,342 --> 02:31:42,503
[GUN COCKS]

1025
02:31:42,677 --> 02:31:46,671
Not so hasty, lieutenant.
We mustn't cheat the hangman.

1026
02:31:50,727 --> 02:31:53,344
What now, major?

1027
02:31:53,896 --> 02:31:56,263
You'll be tried for treason.

1028
02:32:00,069 --> 02:32:03,403
A public trial would be embarrassing.

1029
02:32:03,573 --> 02:32:06,361
Painful, not only for myself...

1030
02:32:06,534 --> 02:32:10,698
...but also for British Intelligence
and Admiral Rolland.

1031
02:32:11,122 --> 02:32:15,537
Perhaps, but not as painful as
that long drop to the end of the rope.

1032
02:32:19,464 --> 02:32:21,046
Well...

1033
02:32:22,383 --> 02:32:27,549
...I seem to have no cards left to play,
do I?

1034
02:32:28,806 --> 02:32:30,046
No, colonel, you don't.

1035
02:32:31,726 --> 02:32:35,390
- Do I have an alternative?
-If you want it.

1036
02:32:43,571 --> 02:32:44,902
Mm.

1037
02:32:47,992 --> 02:32:49,653
Thank you.

1038
02:32:51,079 --> 02:32:54,242
I'll have those books.

1039
02:33:45,800 --> 02:33:48,087
Well, is that it, major?

1040
02:33:48,845 --> 02:33:51,337
Yes, that's it, lieutenant.

1041
02:33:53,015 --> 02:33:54,301
Do me a favor, will you?

1042
02:33:54,475 --> 02:33:58,810
Next time you have one of these things,
keep it an all-British operation.

1043
02:34:00,523 --> 02:34:02,389
I'll try, lieutenant.

1044
02:34:02,413 --> 02:34:14,413
GOPISAHI